SIMPLE: desiderative
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Desiderative
<hw>De*sid"er*a*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>desiderativus</ets>.]</ety> <def>Denoting desire; <as>as,
<ex>desiderative</ex> verbs</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Desiderative</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Desiderative
<hw>De*sid"er*a*tive</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An object of
desire.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>A verb formed from another verb
by a change of termination, and expressing the desire of doing that
which is indicated by the primitive verb.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Desideratum</ent>⟦br⟧
